<div id="comment_status_64239774" class="commentstatus"></div>
<div id="comment_64239774" class="cw">
	<div id="comment_top_64239774" class="commentTop newcomment">
		<div class="title">
			<h4><a id="comment_link_64239774" name="comment_link_64239774" href="//news.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23227110&amp;cid=64239774" onclick="return D2.setFocusComment(64239774)" >Cohesion versus Morale</a>


		 	<span id="comment_score_64239774" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64239774); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>1</a>)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span>Anonymous Coward</span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64239774"></span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64239774"><p>Cohesion: willingness to fight when the enemy starts attacking you.<br>Morale: belief in the cause.</p><p>Volunteer armies typically have high cohesion (that's what you're buying with all those months of training).<br>Conscript armies typically have moderate cohesion, usually because of less training.<br>But what about morale?  What cause justifies fighting for a corrupt government that belittles and mocks you?<br>Would a high-cohesion / low morale army be equivalent to an unpaid mercenary army (the cause being *for the money*)?</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64239774">

</div>
